subject: psu-ng: Power supply class updates for input history
commitMessage:
psu-ng: Power supply class updates for input history

Update the meson files to include the record_manager with the
phosphor-psu-monitor application.

Since we do not want to blindly enable input history for all power
supplies, base the enablement of the feature off of the driver name.
Change the PowerSupply class to require the driver name be passed in,
and pass that down via the PSUManager during the configuration
determination.

Add a server manager to the PSUManager to handle the INPUT HISTORY data
that will be under /org/open_power/sensors.

The INPUT_HISTORY command is handled via a sysfs file in binary format,
so add in a readBinary() base function to allow for mock testing.

Change-Id: Iea163892d5482e6f2dacacfbfa746f605af52ed5
Signed-off-by: Brandon Wyman <bjwyman@gmail.com>

If a PSU is re-inserted, should the prior history be cleared?  I'm not sure what the requirement is here.  If the PSU inserted is different than the one removed, does that matter?

There is a clear() function to the record manager. When a power supply is inserted, it likely will have no records to retrieve via the INPUT_HISTORY command. The data is not stored, as far as I know. When the INPUT_HISTORY response is seen as cleared out, the add() function of the RecordManager sees this, and clears out the records. It will also clear out the data after a sync is done, due to how the record IDs reset.
I don't understand these comments.  Are you referring to the D-Bus ObjectManager interface (not systemd)?  These lines aren't doing anything with that.

I had started out thinking I was going to create a D-Bus ObjectManager interface for each power supply, but only one was needed, and it is up in the PSUManager class/object. I probably should just remove this comment that served as a reminder to myself.

If I am understanding this correctly, each time something has changed (every 30 seconds?) we are going to create two new vectors of 120 items and then copy them into D-Bus.  It is too bad we cannot just add the individual new value vs. copying in the 119 items that didn't change.

Huh... I did not think of that. I was just trying to re-use what we had previously worked with.

The records do not necessarily start out as having 120 items. After power is applied, there will be 0 records to read via INPUT_HISTORY. Every 30 seconds, a new one is added. Eventually, it will reach 120 items in the INPUT_HISTORY data, and 120 items in the record created from that.

At any rate, each time this changes, yeah, the old record with mostly matching data will get replaced with the new record, and all that data gets copied back over to D-Bus.

There is possibly some more efficient way to process these. I am not so sure I want to attempt to refactor that as part of this commit.
the dbus property is an array, and I don't think sdbusplus has any APIs to modify a property piecemeal.

😞
So, not easily possible to be more efficient, but with enough sdbusplus hacking, and more changes here, we could MAYBE get there.

No, this is not a standard PMBus command. I keep explaining what this and other parts of this support are, and then in various spots I end up leaving out some of that detail. :-/

https://github.com/openbmc/linux/blob/0626498c8435ad292c1ba87ede4c98f690fd0ddc/drivers/hwmon/pmbus/ibm-cffps.c#L34

The INPUT_HISTORY command is specific to the IBM Common Form Factor power supplies (as far as I know). It uses the MFR_SPECIFIC_D6 command. "The PMBus protocol reserves 46 command codes for manufacturer specific commands. These commands will be unique to a particular device or manufacturer and allow for unique or proprietary extensions to the PMBus protocol."
